<h1>Elevation</h1>
<p>Elevation is the visual representation of depth in a user interface, helping to create hierarchy, focus, and a sense of spatial relationships between elements.</p>

{{ heading('Shadow and surface', '2') }}
<p>Each elevation level is defined by two properties working in tandem: a <strong>shadow</strong> and a <strong>surface</strong>. Together they ensure depth is always legible — the shadow in light mode, the surface tint in dark mode.</p>

{{ heading('Shadow', '3') }}
<p>The shadow conveys depth using multiple layered drop-shadows with increasing offset and blur — producing a naturalistic light-source impression that grows more pronounced at higher levels. The <code>flat</code> level is the exception: instead of a depth shadow it uses a thin border-like outline to distinguish the element from its background without implying lift.</p>

{{ heading('Surface', '3') }}
<p>The surface is the background of the elevated element. In light mode, surface color stays consistent across all levels — depth is communicated entirely by the shadow. In dark mode, shadows alone provide insufficient contrast, so a white gradient overlay is composited on top of the surface. Its opacity increases with each level, creating a progressively lighter tint that simulates material lift and keeps elevation perceptible across both themes.</p>

{{ heading('Composite elevation tokens', '2') }}
<p>Each level exposes two composite tokens — <code>shadow</code> and <code>surface</code> — that bundle all the underlying semantic color values into a single, ready-to-use output.</p>
